iews -- tChima Osakwe. The Revolutionary Drama and Theatre of Femi Osofisan -- tS. M. Mofokeng. Senkatana -- tVictor N. Gomia and Gilbert S. Ndi, eds Re-writing Pasts, Imagining Futures: Critical Explorations of Contemporary African Fiction and Theater -- tAngelo Gobbato. A Passion for Opera -- tKoulsy Lamko. Bintou Wéré: African Opera -- tMusa Ngqungwana Odyssey of an African Opera Singer -- tMary I. Ingraham, Joseph K. So and Roy Moodley, eds Opera in a Multicultural World: Coloniality, Culture, Performance -- tHilde Roos. The La Traviata Affair: Opera in the Age of Apartheid -- tNaomi André. Black Opera: History, Power, Engagement -- tNaomi André, Donato Somma and Innocentia Jabulisile Mhlambi, eds ‘New Voices in Black South African Opera’ African Studies, vol. 75, no. 10 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCompelling inside views of what characterises opera and music theatre in African and African diasporic contexts.Music is often cited as a central artistic mode in African theatre and performance practices. However, little attention has been paid to music theatre on the continent in general, and to opera in particular, with the exceptions ofa few noted genres, such as Concert Party or the Yorùbá "folk opera" of the 1960s, and the emerging research on opera culture in South Africa. This volume of African Theatre highlights the diversity across the continent from a variety of perspectives - including those of genre, media, and historiography. Above all, it raises questions and encourages debate: What does "opera" mean in African and African diasporic contexts? What are its practices and legacies - colonial, postcolonial and decolonial; what is its relation to the intersectionalities of race and class? How do opera and music theatre reflect, change or obscure social, political and economic realities? How are they connected to educational and cultural institutions, and non-profit organisations? And why is opera contradictorily, at various times, perceived as both "grand" and "elitist, "folk" and "idian", "Eurocentric" and "indigenous"? Contributors also address aesthetic transformation processes, the porousness of genre boundaries and the role of space and place, with examples ranging from Egypt to South Africa, from Uganda to West Africa and the USA. The playscript in this volume is We Take Care of Our Own by Zainabu Jallo GUEST EDITORS: Christine Matzke, Lena van der Hoven, Christopher Odhiambo & Hilde Roos Series Editors: Yvette Hutchison, Reader, Department of Theatre & Performance Studies, University of Warwick; Chukwuma Okoye, Reader in African Theatre & Performance University of Ibadan; Jane Plastow, Professor of African Theatre, University of Leeds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican drama (English). 0aMusical theaterzAfricaxHistory and criticism. 0aOperazAfrica. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh  aAfrican diaspora.  aAfrican theatre.  acultural impact.  adiversity.  amusic theatre.  aopera.1 aAdewole, Funmi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgboluaje, Oladipo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmin, Nora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArendse, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiangong, Pepetual Mforbe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunton, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFourie, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFourie, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJallo, Zainabu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc